 To solve the system of linear equations, we can use substitution or elimination techniques. Let's use the elimination method.
We can subtract the second equation from the first to eliminate n and solve for m. Let's see how that works.
\begin{align*}
(3m + 4n) - (m + n) & = 47 - 15 \\
2m + 3n & = 32
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
2m & = 32 - 3n \\
m & = \frac{32 - 3n}{2}
\end{align*}
Now that we have m in terms of n, we can substitute it back into one of the original equations and solve for n.
\begin{align*}
m + n & = 15 \\
\frac{32 - 3n}{2} + n & = 15 \\
32 - 3n + 2n & = 30 \\
-n & = -2 \\
n & = 2
\end{align*}
Finally, we can substitute the value of n back into one of the original equations to solve for m.
\begin{align*}
m & = \frac{32 - 3n}{2} \\
m & = \frac{32 - 3(2)}{2} \\
m & = \frac{32 - 6}{2} \\
m & = \frac{26}{2} \\
m & = 13
\end{align*}
Therefore, the value of m is <answer> $13$ </answer>

 Hey, the first thing I did was I took away the $n$ from both sides. First let us subtract $n$ from each side. So we have, \begin{align*}
3m+4n {\cancel{-n}}=-n\\ 3m{\boldsymbol{+}}{\cancelto{\,\,2}{3}}n=47{\cancel{-n}}\\ 3m+{\boldsymbol{3}}n=47-n
\end{align*} However, we still have $n$ on the right side, so I divided each side by $3$.\begin{align*}
\frac{{\boldsymbol{3}}m+3n}{{\boldsymbol{3}}}=\frac{{47-n}}{{\boldsymbol{3}}}\\ m+n=\frac{47}{{\,\,3}}-\frac{{n}}{{\,\,3}}
\end{align*} Looking at the second equation, we know that $m+n=15$, so we can subtract $\frac{n}{{\,\,3}}$ from each side.\begin{align*} {\boldsymbol{15}}-\frac{{n}}{{\,\,3}}{\boldsymbol{=}}\frac{{47}}{{\,\,3}}-\frac{{n}}{{\,\,3}}-\frac{{n}}{{\,\,3}}\\ 15{\boldsymbol{-}}\cancel{\frac{n}{{\,\,3}}}=\frac{{47}}{{\,\,3}}{\boldsymbol{-}}\cancelto{{\,\,\frac{2}{3}}}{{\frac{{n}}{{\,\,3}}}}\\ 15-{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}}}{\boldsymbol{=}}{\boldsymbol{\frac{{47}}{{\,\,3}}-{\boldsymbol{\frac{2}{3}}}}}\\ 15-{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}}}{\boldsymbol{=}}{\boldsymbol{\frac{{45}}{{\,\,3}}}}\\ 15-{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}}}=15
\end{align*} Last but not least, we do the opposite of subtracting, so we add $\frac{n}{{\,\,3}}$ to each side.\begin{align*}
15+{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}}}={\boldsymbol{15}}+{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}}}\\ 15+{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}}}={\boldsymbol{15}}+{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}}}\\ m={\boldsymbol{15}}-{\boldsymbol{\frac{n}{3}+}\frac{n}{{\,\,3}}}\\ m={\boldsymbol{15}}\end{align*} Hence, the answer is $\boxed{m=15}$

